We apologize for posting this on a Friday evening but we just received final guidance from the state. We have had a positive COVID-19 case at Brooke High School with one of our students.

Following our protocol, we have contacted Mike Bolen, Brooke County Health Department, State Superintendent Clayton Burch and his team to update them of our situation. Based on the information we have received, Mike Bolen at the Brooke County Health Department and Carol Cipoletti have conducted contact tracing and all persons who have been in contact with the individual will be quarantined and tested for COVID-19. Based on the guidance received, Brooke High School will continue to operate as normal on the hybrid schedule.

We will communicate any modifications or changes to all of our operations. Unless you see information from my office, everything else is speculation or rumors.

PRESS RELEASE
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE

Brooke County Schools Delays start for Brooke Intermediate North and Brooke Middle School

September 5, 2020

Brooke County Schools has a staff member from Brooke Intermediate North who has tested positive for COVID-19. Contact tracing has been conducted and all persons who have been in contact with the individual will be quarantined and tested for COVID-19. We are currently working with Mike Bolen, Brooke County Health Department, WV Regional Health Department, Clayton Burch, West Virginia State Superintendent of Schools, and West Virginia Department of Education. Brooke County Schools will delay the in-person instruction at Brooke Intermediate North and Brooke Middle School at least one week, September 8- September 11 in order to receive COVID-19 tests results. All other schools will operate on the hybrid schedule beginning Tuesday, September 8, 2020.

Brooke County Schools Press Release:

With sincere regrets, the Brooke High School's graduation scheduled for July 23, 2020, has been canceled. After conversions with Mr. Michael Bolen at the Brooke County Health Department, school officials believe canceling the ceremony is in the best interest of our students, staff, and community. Currently, there are 19 active cases of COVID19 in Brooke County. School officials are not willing to take any unnecessary chances that could result in spreading this virus further. We apologize for any inconvenience.

post_text:
Brooke County Schools is pleased to announce our 2019-2020 Teacher of the Year, Dianna Cornett. Mrs. Cornett currently teaches second grade at Brooke Primary North. She has been an educator for the past 31 years, spending 25 of those in Brooke County Schools.
She has taught at Brooke High School and three Brooke County elementary schools including Edgewood School, Colliers Primary School, and Brooke Primary South. She earned a Bachelor of Arts from West Liberty State College and a Master of Arts in Special Education from West Virginia University.
Dianna will now contend for the West Virginia State Teacher of the Year.

post_text: Announcement: Class of 2020 students and parents. No decision has been made concerning the graduation ceremony for the Class of 2020. We would like to wait until we know for sure that the governors stay at home order remains in place for the remainder of the school year. No matter what, we want our seniors to graduate in the gym at Brooke High School with parents, siblings and relatives cheering them on!!! We are planning backup graduation plans, but we are not ready to cancel the important face-to-face, personal graduation ceremony. If you have any questions, please email Jeffrey Crook at jcrook@k12.wv.us. Thanks and stay safe!

This is a message from Ms. Yost, the yearbook adviser at Brooke High School. Currently, 62 seniors have submitted photos for the 2020 yearbook. Because of current health concerns, I have decided to move the due date for senior photos to June 1st. Please remember: To list your activities with your photo and to have your name printed exactly as you want it to appear, you must join Google Classroom 22imts4 and complete the form "Senior Activities 2020." This is also where you can include your "senior quote."
I cannot stress enough the importance of looking out for your neighbor during this time. Remind your senior friends! Email all senior photos to me at eyost@k12.wv.us.

post_text:
Senior Photo Guidelines - Class of 2020
Due Date: Thursday, April 16, 2020

Specifications:
1. Only COLOR portraits will be accepted (no black & white photos)
2. You may NOT include anything in your photo that you are not allowed to have in school.
3. Please maintain an appropriate facial expression in your photo.
4. Formal portraits are preferred.
5. All portraits are to be VERTICAL in nature.
6. The photo must be taken at 300 dpi resolution.
7. The photo must be 2.25" by 3.25" in dimension.
8. Only digital copies will be accepted.
9. No watermarks may appear on your photo.

Once these conditions are met, please email a copy of the photo to Emily Yost, BHS Yearbook Adviser, at eyost@k12.wv.us

It is YOUR RESPONSIBILITY TO:
** Meet the Yearbook's deadline.
** Dress appropriately.
** Communicate with your photographer.
** Ensure your photographer has
-- emailed your acceptable photo, or
-- provided you with a digital copy of your acceptable photo to turn in.

The College Board
March 16 at 2:26 PM ¬∑

The College Board is developing tools to mitigate the impact of school closures on students in the Advanced Placement Program. All AP students and teachers will be able to draw on the free online resources that were provided to every AP classroom this fall. Additional resources will be made easily accessible to AP students and teachers through mobile phones and other devices. These include free online AP lessons and review sessions from some of the top AP teachers in the country.

The AP program is finalizing streamlined AP exam options that would allow students to test at home, depending on the situation in May. We‚Äôre working to give every AP student the opportunity to claim the credit they‚Äôve earned. The AP Program will communicate the details of these additional solutions to educators and students by March 20.

The College Board‚Äôs focus will remain on student safety and ensuring all students have the tools they need to work, and opportunities to receive the credit they have earned, during this challenging time.

More details: http://spr.ly/61861srPq.

All Brooke County Schools will operate on a 2- hour delay for Friday, March 13, 2020. This delay is necessary to provide teachers and staff an opportunity to plan for five additional snow packet days in the event schools are closed for an extended period of time. This is due to the current health concerns we are facing regarding COVID19 with the Brooke County Schools community. Announcement: Good morning! We had a power breaker switch fail at Brooke High School in the kitchen this morning. In order to fix the switch, we will need to shutdown power in part of the school building. The repair should take roughly 15 minutes. All students will remain in their classrooms until the repair is complete.

All students are safe and secure...the interruption to instruction will be minimal.

If you have any questions, please contact the board of education office at 304-737-3481. Thanks!

post_text: Math4Life is a state initiative that Brooke County Schools is involved in. We are working on several events for this school year that involve our teachers and your children. Our county teachers are involved in trainings offered through the state‚Äôs Math4Life speaker series to help improve math instruction. For the students, we are most excited about a One Book, One Community event where students will read the same book and be involved with activities surrounding the theme of the book pertaining to math skills. We hope you see our effort in working with our county‚Äôs students to make mathematics more of a life skill.

The Yearbook Program at Brooke High School the arrival of the 50th anniversary edition of Crossroads for 2020. This year‚Äôs book will feature a ‚Äúthrowback‚Äù cover and a number of feature articles on ‚ÄúThe Way Things Were.‚Äù

Ms. Yost seeks reflections from 1970 alumni. Any graduates from that year can send their reflections on the first year of Brooke High School to eyost@k12.wv.us. You may wish to consider a favorite teacher, activity, or group of friends ‚Äì or simply life in 1969 ‚Äì 1970 versus today. Your contributions may be printed, along with your 1970 senior photo, in the 2020 yearbook. Please also include any maiden names so that Ms. Yost can find you in your yearbook.

post_text: BPN & BPS K-2 teachers, ECCATs, administrators participated in 3 intensive days of Success for All training this week.
